-- Hong Kong Stocks Decline as Property Shares Slide
-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 2013-10-24T01:37:45Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-10-24/hong-kong-stocks-decline-as-property-shares-slide.html
Hong Kong  stocks  fell, with the
benchmark index extending the biggest loss in three weeks, as
developers declined. Investors are waiting on preliminary China
manufacturing data for September to be released this morning.  The  Hang Seng Index  slid 0.8 percent to 22,825,00 as of
9:34 a.m. in Hong Kong, with all but four shares on the 50-member gauge declining. The  Hang Seng China Enterprises Index (HSCEI) ,
also known as the H-share index, lost 1.2 percent to 10,332.41.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  climbed 16 percent from this year’s low
in June through yesterday amid signs  China’s economy  is
stabilizing. The equity benchmark traded at 11 times estimated
earnings yesterday, compared with 15.8 for the Standard & Poor’s
500 Index.  The HSBC Holdings Plc and Markit Economics flash purchasing
managers’ index on Chinese manufacturing due today is expected
to rise to 50.4 in October from 50.2 in September, according to
a Bloomberg survey of economists.  Standard Chartered Plc raised its 2013 forecast for China
growth to 7.6 percent from 7.5 percent, with the official target
for 7.5 percent expansion this year. Data last week showed the
economy emerged from a two-quarter slowdown in the three months
through September.  Futures on the  S&P 500  added 0.1 percent. The U.S. equity
gauge dropped 0.5 percent yesterday as valuations reached an
almost four-year high and forecasts at companies from
Caterpillar Inc. to Broadcom Corp. disappointed investors.  To contact the reporter on this story:
